<div id="review_77163335" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/77163335" />
    <a title="Emily" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1889783-emily"><img alt="Emily" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1426205490p2/1889783.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/77163335?book_show_action=true">Nov 08, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Emily" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Emily" href="/user/show/1889783-emily">Emily</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1889783-emily?shelf=2008">2008</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer77163335" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2932893193678239716">In <a href='http://www.auntiemomo.com/cakeordeath/d2ktranscription.html' rel='nofollow noopener'>&quot;Dress to Kill&quot;</a>, Eddie Izzard says:<blockquote>But there were other mass murderers that got away with it! Stalin killed many millions, died in his bed, well done there; Pol Pot killed 1.7 million Cambodians, died under house arrest at age 72, well done indeed! And the reason we let them get away with it is because they killed their own people, and we&apos;re sort of fine with that. ... Hitler killed people next door... “Oh... stupid man!” After a couple of years, we won&apos;t stand for that, will we?</blockquote>I thought of </span>
  <span id="freeText2932893193678239716" style="display:none">In <a href="http://www.auntiemomo.com/cakeordeath/d2ktranscription.html" rel="nofollow noopener">"Dress to Kill"</a>, Eddie Izzard says:<blockquote>But there were other mass murderers that got away with it! Stalin killed many millions, died in his bed, well done there; Pol Pot killed 1.7 million Cambodians, died under house arrest at age 72, well done indeed! And the reason we let them get away with it is because they killed their own people, and we're sort of fine with that. ... Hitler killed people next door... “Oh... stupid man!” After a couple of years, we won't stand for that, will we?</blockquote>I thought of this line often while I was reading <i>"A Problem from Hell": America and the Age of Genocide</i> because Izzard in his own way really nails the sad conclusion that you come to reading Power's book, which is that it's hard to get people to care about genocides, and, even if you do succeed in that, by the time you've proven your case, it's too late for many victims. Power analyzes the lackluster response of the United States to several post-WWII genocides, and concludes that our current system functions properly according to its own flawed purpose.<br /><br />That goal is to involve the U.S. only when its own interests are threatened--or even to stand deliberately aside when the perpetrators of a genocide are the enemies of an opponent (the genocidal enemies of our enemies are our friends?). For example, Power shows how Iraq's stance against Iran prevented the U.S. from intervening when Saddam Hussein gassed the Kurds. <br /><br />Power explains the history of the term "genocide" and how it grew up in the aftermath of the Holocaust; although that event inspired interest in and commitment to stopping genocide, it also gave people a very specific idea of what qualified as genocide. When later events didn't "measure up" to the Holocaust in terms of the percentage of the population killed or the means used (killing versus sterilization, for example), observers got tangled up in terminology and excused themselves from decisive action.<br /><br />Before reading this book, I was familiar with Power's ideas from her articles in <a href="http://www.theatlantic.com/doc/200109/power-genocide" rel="nofollow noopener">The Atlantic Monthly</a> and elsewhere. I'm making the odd choice to give a Pulitzer Prize-winning and very well-reviewed book a not very good rating (for those who actually put any stock in my ratings...). The reason is that I felt this book was poorly edited: with the main text clocking in at over 500 pages, Power had a hard time strongly pulling her themes together under the weight of so much documentation and detail. I think that any nonexpert who isn't trying to marshal these specific facts would get her message better from one of her articles.<br /><br />And the message isn't a very happy one. Indeed, when you consider the forces that Power describes, it seems even less likely to me that the U.S. would intervene in, say, Darfur, than it did before. The book is a history more t</span>
  <a data-text-id="2932893193678239716" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


