        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3142831980" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3680601088308480068">Very tough book to read but one I think everyone entering the United States Foreign Service should read. It really highlights America&apos;s lack of involvement in stopping genocide, which is nothing new. But what is depressing is when America hinders other communities from helping out, like not lifting the Arms Embargo so Bosnian Muslims could defend themselves. <br/>Each chapter is well researched but Power writes in a way that isn&apos;t so academic that the average reader is bored or confused. <br/>She chronicl</span>
  <span id="freeText3680601088308480068" style="display:none">Very tough book to read but one I think everyone entering the United States Foreign Service should read. It really highlights America's lack of involvement in stopping genocide, which is nothing new. But what is depressing is when America hinders other communities from helping out, like not lifting the Arms Embargo so Bosnian Muslims could defend themselves. <br />Each chapter is well researched but Power writes in a way that isn't so academic that the average reader is bored or confused. <br />She chronicles the major genocides of the 20th century up to 2001 and America's role in or lack of role in stopping them (Armenian, Holocaust, Cambodia, Kurds, Bosnia, Rwanda, Kosovo).<br />I believe ultimately her point and one I continue to say, is the moniker "Never Again" is a nice platitude but evidence shows that again and again we allow genocide to occur. I think the "Never Again" phrase should have a caveat, "Never Again" only if it is people who look like us and practice our same religion. If you are dark skinned and not Christian, you can forget America coming to the rescue. <br />The one aspect of this otherwise very depressing book that I enjoyed was how she highlights the people who fought against the tide to try to get the world to pay attention, to get America to pay attention and do something. I was surprised to learn about how Joe Biden and Bob Dole were so instrumental in forcing America to act to end the Bosnian war. Also the Ambassador in Turkey during the Armenian genocide trying to get America to act. <br />Not an easy read or for the feint of heart but really should be a necessary read, if only so we Americans can realize we can't have the moral high ground unless we act. </span>
  <a data-text-id="3680601088308480068" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


