    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3170690781" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3170690781" />
    <a title="DavidA" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/82475844-davida"><img alt="DavidA" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1551274304p2/82475844.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3170690781?book_show_action=true">Feb 16, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="DavidA" class="user" itemprop="url" name="DavidA" href="/user/show/82475844-davida">DavidA</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3170690781" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17625868167876688153">Several years ago, my wife and I visited the United States Holocaust Museum in Washington, DC. When we came across the aerial photographs taken of the concentration camps, we paused and thought: We knew… <br/><br/>Having enjoyed reading The Education of An Idealist, I picked up this book at a used book sale. Given the content, I knew it would be an emotionally difficult book to read. As a senior majoring in history at Kent State in the 1960s, we read The Rise and Fall of the Third Reich (a weighty book) i</span>
  <span id="freeText17625868167876688153" style="display:none">Several years ago, my wife and I visited the United States Holocaust Museum in Washington, DC. When we came across the aerial photographs taken of the concentration camps, we paused and thought: We knew… <br /><br />Having enjoyed reading The Education of An Idealist, I picked up this book at a used book sale. Given the content, I knew it would be an emotionally difficult book to read. As a senior majoring in history at Kent State in the 1960s, we read The Rise and Fall of the Third Reich (a weighty book) in one class. Today, we could have read A Problem From Hell. <br /><br />The stories of genocide in Cambodia, Iraq, Bosnia, Rwanda, Srebrenica and Kosovo were emotionally gripping. <br /><br />What gave me hope are the stories of Lemkin, Proxmire, Dole and so many state department officers. But this is a sad tale of American indifference. To not intervene when men are killed in horrible ways and mothers and daughters are raped and then killed leaves one without words. <br /><br />Today, there is Syrian President Bashar Al Assad and his use of chemical weapons. There is the genocide of the Rohingya Muslims in Myanmar. And each day we read about the Russian and Syrian bombings of hospitals. <br /><br />Samantha Power is an outstanding writer. Her stories are eloquently written. Her book begs one question: What does it take? <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="17625868167876688153" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

